
DISC — Operational Behavioral Decoding Guide

BASIC PRINCIPLE
4 styles, 4 colors. Each person is a unique combination, usually with 1 or 2 dominant styles. DISC does not put people in boxes: it provides a common language for better communication.

────────────────────────────────────────

🔴 D — DOMINANT | Keyword: RESULTS

BEHAVIORAL SIGNATURE
Direct · Ambitious · Competitive · Decisive · Driven · Authoritative · Independent

WHAT MOTIVATES THEM
Challenges · Power · Control · Autonomy · Winning · Concrete Results · Efficiency

WHAT THEY FEAR
Loss of control · Failure · Being dominated · Stagnation · Indecision

UNDER PRESSURE, THEY...
Become authoritative · Grow impatient · Attack or take flight · Increase control

HOW THEY COMMUNICATE
→ Gets straight to the point, short and concise sentences
→ Asserts more than questions
→ Speaks loudly and quickly, direct and blunt tone
→ Firm handshake, steady and confronting gaze

HOW TO COMMUNICATE WITH THEM ✅
→ Get straight to the point: conclusion first, details only if requested
→ Talk results, facts, and figures (no emotions)
→ Provide options: they want to maintain control over the final decision
→ Respect their time: no small talk
→ Show your competence: this builds trust and reduces their need to micromanage

ABSOLUTELY AVOID ⚠️
→ Long and emotional speeches
→ Lack of preparation or confidence
→ Questioning their authority publicly

POINTS OF VIGILANCE
May appear cold, arrogant, or abrupt. Their aggressiveness is a defense mechanism, not an end in itself.

────────────────────────────────────────

🟡 I — INFLUENTIAL | Keyword: RECOGNITION

BEHAVIORAL SIGNATURE
Enthusiastic · Optimistic · Sociable · Persuasive · Charming · Spontaneous · Creative

WHAT MOTIVATES THEM
Attention · Popularity · Pleasure · Novelty · Social interaction · Being the center of attention

WHAT THEY FEAR
Rejection · Isolation · Being poorly perceived · Boredom · Routine · Loss of influence

UNDER PRESSURE, THEY...
Exaggerate · Create diversions · Isolate if they feel unloved · Become theatrical

HOW THEY COMMUNICATE
→ Tells stories, digresses easily
→ Theatrical tone, expressive voice, lots of gestures
→ Talks about themselves, seeks humor and connection
→ Smiling, relaxed and open posture

HOW TO COMMUNICATE WITH THEM ✅
→ Build a connection first: small talk is welcome and necessary
→ Value their ideas and congratulate them sincerely
→ Speak about impact and visibility: what others will see, the central role they will play
→ Use stories and anecdotes to maintain attention
→ Do not drown them in technical details or procedures

ABSOLUTELY AVOID ⚠️
→ A cold, purely technical approach
→ Ignoring or minimizing their contribution
→ Solitary tasks without visibility or recognition

POINTS OF VIGILANCE
May appear disorganized, over-commit, or scatter efforts. Link boring tasks to a concrete social reward.

────────────────────────────────────────

🟢 S — STEADY | Keyword: SECURITY

BEHAVIORAL SIGNATURE
Calm · Patient · Loyal · Cooperative · Predictable · Humble · Attentive

WHAT MOTIVATES THEM
Harmony · Stability · Support · Consensus · Sincere relationships · Being useful to the team

WHAT THEY FEAR
Conflicts · Rapid and unforeseen change · Insecurity · Letting others down · Aggressiveness

UNDER PRESSURE, THEY...
Withdraw · Internalize · Procrastinate → risk of the "pressure cooker effect" (sudden explosion after silent accumulation)

HOW THEY COMMUNICATE
→ Listens more than speaks
→ Calm and soft tone, slow pace, little variation
→ Keeps opinions to themselves
→ Avoids direct eye contact, slow and measured gestures

HOW TO COMMUNICATE WITH THEM ✅
→ Be patient and sincere: no pressure, no rushing
→ Explain the "why" behind every decision or change
→ Introduce changes gradually, emphasizing the available support
→ Value their contribution to the team and their loyalty
→ Create a safe space for them to express doubts without fear of judgment

ABSOLUTELY AVOID ⚠️
→ Rushing them or imposing a pace that is too fast
→ Ignoring their silent discomfort (real danger in the medium term)
→ Imposing decisions without explanation

POINTS OF VIGILANCE
Their silence does not mean agreement. Passive in appearance, they can "explode" if accumulated pressure becomes unbearable.

────────────────────────────────────────

🔵 C — COMPLIANT (Conscientious) | Keyword: QUALITY

BEHAVIORAL SIGNATURE
Precise · Analytical · Methodical · Rigorous · Perfectionist · Factual · Organized

WHAT MOTIVATES THEM
Quality · Accuracy · Rules and standards · Expertise · Being right · Having clear structure

WHAT THEY FEAR
Error · Criticism of their work · Chaos · Ambiguity · Decisions made by "gut feeling"

UNDER PRESSURE, THEY...
Avoid · Rationalize · Retreat into details · Become critical or rigid → risk of "analysis paralysis"

HOW THEY COMMUNICATE
→ Structured, factual speech, precise vocabulary
→ Asks many questions: "Why?" "How?" "On what basis?"
→ Slow speech, stable voice, little emotion
→ Little gesturing, controlled posture, formal handshake

HOW TO COMMUNICATE WITH THEM ✅
→ Be structured and precise: data, evidence, factual figures
→ Prefer writing: they need time to analyze
→ Anticipate their questions and prepare exhaustive answers
→ Clearly define expected standards (what "good enough" means)
→ Validate their expertise and the quality of their work explicitly

ABSOLUTELY AVOID ⚠️
→ Generalizations and approximations
→ Decisions based on intuition or emotion
→ Excessive time pressure without complete resources

POINTS OF VIGILANCE
May fall into "analysis paralysis." Needs external validation to finalize and move forward.

────────────────────────────────────────

QUICK DECODING: WHICH PROFILE IS IN FRONT OF ME?

🔴 D | Speaks fast, decides fast, interrupts, takes the lead
🟡 I | Tells anecdotes, seeks to build a connection, enthusiastic
🟢 S | Listens, calm, takes a step back, nods without imposing
🔵 C | Asks precise questions, requests data, takes notes

────────────────────────────────────────

GOLDEN RULE OF COMMUNICATION BY PROFILE

🔴 D — Start with the conclusion, the result
Key argument: "Here is what this brings you concretely"
What kills the relationship: details and emotion

🟡 I — Start with the connection, the warmth
Key argument: "You will be on the front line, the team will love it"
What kills the relationship: a cold and technical approach

🟢 S — Start with security, trust
Key argument: "We are going gradually, you are supported"
What kills the relationship: rushing and imposed change

🔵 C — Start with facts, logic
Key argument: "Here is the data that justifies this decision"
What kills the relationship: approximations and intuition

────────────────────────────────────────

MANAGEMENT: MOTIVATING AND DELEGATING BY PROFILE

🔴 D
Levers: Challenges, autonomy, responsibilities, ambitious goals
Delegation: Give the goal, let them decide on the "how"

🟡 I
Levers: Public recognition, creativity, collaboration
Delegation: Involve them in visible projects and team moments

🟢 S
Levers: Stable environment, valued loyalty, group utility
Delegation: Support change, explain every step

🔵 C
Levers: Recognized expertise, valued quality, clear standards
Delegation: Provide all resources and define success criteria

────────────────────────────────────────

SALES: ADAPTING YOUR PITCH

🔴 D | What they buy: A competitive advantage, time savings
Decisive argument: ROI, efficiency, quick results

🟡 I | What they buy: An experience, a social opportunity
Decisive argument: Testimonials, enthusiasm, image

🟢 S | What they buy: Trust, continuity
Decisive argument: Support, references, stability

🔵 C | What they buy: Evidence, a reliable solution
Decisive argument: Data, studies, guarantees, comparisons

────────────────────────────────────────

RECRUITMENT: WHAT EACH PROFILE LOOKS FOR

🔴 D | Ideal environment: Autonomy, challenge, rapid evolution
What to promise: Responsibilities and direct impact

🟡 I | Ideal environment: Tight-knit team, variety, visibility
What to promise: Recognition and a positive atmosphere

🟢 S | Ideal environment: Stability, clear mission, benevolent team
What to promise: Security and sustainable support

🔵 C | Ideal environment: Rigor, high standards, clear roles
What to promise: Valued expertise and complete resources

